Here's a typical `MauiProgram.cs` setup:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

namespace MyMauiApp;

public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder
            .UseMauiApp<App>()
            .ConfigureFonts(fonts =>
            {
                fonts.AddFont("OpenSans-Regular.ttf", "OpenSansRegular");
            });

        // HttpClient — singleton so connections are reused (avoids socket exhaustion)
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<HttpClient>();

        // Data service — singleton because it wraps HttpClient and holds no
        // per-user/per-page state; one instance serves the whole app
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels — transient so each navigation gets fresh state
        // (no stale data from a previous visit)
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages — transient to match their ViewModels; each navigation
        // creates a new page with a new ViewModel injected
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

#if DEBUG
        builder.Logging.AddDebug();
#endif

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

### Why each lifetime?

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `HttpClient` | **Singleton** | Reuses TCP connections; avoids socket exhaustion from repeated `new HttpClient()` |
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Stateless API wrapper — one instance is enough; shares the singleton `HttpClient` |
| `*ViewModel` | **Transient** | Each navigation should get a clean ViewModel with no leftover state |
| `*Page` | **Transient** | Matches ViewModel lifetime; a new page resolves a new ViewModel via constructor injection |

### When you'd choose differently

- **Scoped** — not commonly used in MAUI (no built-in request scope like ASP.NET), but useful if you create your own `IServiceScope` per navigation.
- **Singleton ViewModels** — only if a page must survive navigation (e.g., a persistent dashboard). Be careful with memory.
- For production, consider `IHttpClientFactory` (via `AddHttpClient<IDataService, DataService>()`) instead of a raw singleton `HttpClient` — it handles DNS rotation and pooling automatically.
